Biteme

Target IP: 10.10.22.35

Stay out of my server!

Scanning


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP. I will start enumeration with the HTTP application on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP


The default Apache webpage is displayed for this application. However, doing a directory search with the command gobuster dir -u http://10.10.22.35/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt -x php,html,txt finds an interesting directory called /console. And browsing to this directory shows the webpage above. I tried spraying different default credentials such as admin:admin and root:root, but it did not work. Time to enumerate further. I find the captcha interesting.


Viewing the source-code of this HTML page shows the interesting JavaScript code above. It is obfuscated, but some parts can still be read. The function handleSubmit() is interesting.


Executing the function handleSubmit() at the browser console shows the message above. Two usernames are obtained here: fred and jason. Syntax highlighting, huh? PHP code can be rendered directly on a browser. These files are stored in a .phps file.


Searching for the different .phps files using the command gobuster dir -u http://10.10.22.35/console/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt -x phps shows the entries above.


The index.phps contains the code above. The highlighted code above is the most important, as the function is_valid_pwd and is_valid_user are used to check the user input for valid credential. I will need to find the source code of these two functions.


And bingo! The two functions are above at functions.phps. The username is converted using the function bin2hex, so this can be decoded easily by decoding the input from hex to ASCII. The second function is tough. It looks like the password input is converted to an MD5 hash and the last three digits of the hash are checked to ensure it contains 001.


The configs.phps contain the code above.

The username 6a61736f6e5f746573745f6163636f756e74 can be decoded. Using Cyberchef, I managed to decode it to jason_test_account. Now I have a username. Time to find a possible password with a hash ending in 001.


Since md5 is used for the password authentication, I used this too for my Python script. I created the script above to find possible passwords from rockyou.txt that ends with a md5 hash of 001. Each password in this text file contains a newline, so I will remove it.


Running my Python script shows the password violet is possible as its md5 hash ends in 001.



Using the credential jason_test_account:violet, I gained access. However, it is asking for the MFA code. Viewing the source-code of this page contains juicy information.


There is another obfuscated JavaScript code with the function name handleSubmit(), as shown above.


And executing the code handleSubmit() shows the message above. No brute force protection, eh? Time to bruteforce it.


Now I have the PHPSESSID, I can use automated tools for the bruteforce as this new user.

numbers = open("numbers.txt", "w")
for i in range(1000, 9999+1):
    numbers.write(str(i))
    numbers.write("\n")
numbers.close()
numbers = open("numbers.txt", "w")
for i in range(1000, 9999+1):
    numbers.write(str(i))
    numbers.write("\n")
numbers.close()

Using the Python code above, I generated the numbers between 1000-9999 for the bruteforce attack against the MFA.


And bingo! Using the command hydra -l jason_test_account -P numbers.txt 10.10.22.35 http-post-form "/console/mfa.php:code=^PASS^:H=Cookie:PHPSESSID=j1mbhn65n502og7pu9b194js2c; pwd=violet; user=jason_test_account:Incorrect code", I bruteforced the MFA and received the correct code as 2902.


And now I have access to the web application finally. It looks like I can use File browser and File viewer options.


Using the File viewer against /etc/passwd works, as shown above. Users jason and fred exist.


After some enumeration, I managed to obtain the SSH key of user jason using the input /home/jason/.ssh/id_rsa. It looks like the SSH key is encrypted, so I will need to use ssh2john to decrypt it.


I copied the SSH to my machine and ran ssh2john to obtain the hash, and crack the passphrase. Now I have the SSH password 1a2b3c4d for the user jason.

Exploitation & Privilege Escalation


And now I have a foothold on the target machine.


Running sudo -l shows the interesting PE vector above.


Using the command sudo -u fred bash, I escalated my privileges to the user fred from jason. This new user can run the interesting command above. I will need to find the fail2ban config file now.


Running the command find / -writable -type f 2>/dev/null shows the entry /etc/fail2ban/action.d/iptables-multiport.conf. And running cat on it shows it is the config file of fail2ban.


And I have write privileges over this file.


I will modify the actionban option of fail2ban.


Using vim, I inserted a bash reverse shell at actionban option. And I restarted the service using the command sudo -u root /bin/systemctl restart fail2ban for the change to take place.


And now I have a root shell. GG. In the picture above, there are three terminals:

  • Terminal one (top) is responsible for restarting the service after the bash reverse shell script is inserted.
  • Terminal two (middle) is used for entering wrong credential against the SSH application, so the actionban option is executed (aka, the bash reverse shell connection).
  • Terminal three (bottom) is where I obtain the root reverse shell connection.
